I feel like it's time to take a course in dynamic programming, because I often run into problems that block me for precisely this reason. 
And quite a few of them are among the most difficult mid-tier problems.

But you can approach it in a different, more understandable way - look at all the versions of possible movements (by s + s trick), 
and check each of them for the number of necessary changes based on the pattern 101 and 010
"""

# https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-number-of-flips-to-make-the-binary-string-alternating/solutions/7631254/aot-beats-100-see-it-in-action-by-nandin-t6i0/
class Solution:
    def minFlips(self, s: str) -> int:
        size = len(s)
        double_string = s + s
        ans = size
        mis0 = 0

        for i in range(2 * size):
            expected0 = '0' if i % 2 == 0 else '1'
            if double_string[i] != expected0:
                mis0 += 1

            if i >= size:
                left = i - size
                if double_string[left] != ('0' if left % 2 == 0 else '1'):
                    mis0 -= 1

            if i >= size - 1:
                ans = min(ans, min(mis0, size - mis0))

        return ans
